In this section, we create all the variables we want to compare in our bivariate analysis. We use the existing CanALE data to run calculations and create new combinations of variables in additional columns, which we will use later in the rest of the analysis. We do this using the mutate() function to create new columns.

Variables: ale_index pct_active_transit (walk + bike to work) pct_under40k pct_over40k pct_Imm (immigrant) AvVal AvRent

# plot(CanALE_space[37])
# plot(CanALE_space[33])

CanALE_space <- CanALE_space %>% 
  rowwise() %>% 
  mutate(pct_Imm = Imm/Pop) %>% 
  mutate(pct_walked = Walked/Mode) %>% 
  mutate(pct_biked = Bicycle/Mode) %>% 
  mutate(pct_pubtrans = Pubtrans/Mode) %>% 
  mutate(pct_active_trans = sum(Bicycle, Walked)/Mode) %>% 
  mutate(pct_pubwalkbike = sum(Pubtrans, Bicycle, Walked)/Mode) %>% 
  mutate(pct_under40k = sum(Under_5k, IN5k_10k, IN10k_15k, IN15k, IN20k_25k, IN25k_30k, IN30k_35k, IN35k_40k)/Households) %>% 
   mutate(pct_over40k = sum(IN40k_45k, IN45k_50k, IN50k_60k, IN60k_70k, IN70k_80k, IN80k_90k,
                            IN90k, INOver100k)/Households) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  st_as_sf

In this section, we assign a bivariate color scale to each pair of variables to analyze. Because of the structure of the code, each pair needs to be coded separately to its own color scale so that we will late be able to compare bivariate analyses.

Here we extract quantiles from each variable. The quantiles are extracted by splitting the variable values into three classes. This distributes each variable into the same number of quantiles, which we will then be able to cross with a second variable to create our bivariate analysis.

## variable quantiles

#bivariate <- cbind(ro, house_poor$percent_house_poor)

# define number of classes
no_classes <- 3

# extract quantiles
quantiles_ale_index <- CanALE_space %>% drop_na() %>%
  pull(ale_index) %>% 
  quantile(probs = seq(0, 1, length.out = no_classes + 1)) %>%
  as.vector() # to remove names of quantiles, so idx below is numeric

quantiles_pct_active_trans <- CanALE_space %>% drop_na() %>%
  pull(pct_active_trans) %>% 
  quantile(probs = seq(0, 1, length.out = no_classes + 1)) %>%
  as.vector() # to remove names of quantiles, so idx below is numeric

quantiles_pct_under40k <- CanALE_space %>% drop_na() %>%

In order to use the quantiles for the analysis, we must combine the pairs of variable quantiles previously generated. We use cbind() to do this for two variables at a time. We then join by the color scale previously assigned to that variable pairing and pair by the group assigned in order to be able to map the variables according to their quantile color schemes in the next section.

Merge datasets, calculate quantiles, and add new field for match id for coloring

CanALE_space

In this code, we assign bivariate color scale fills to eah quantile variable pair. We use the mean quantiles created in the previous code section to separate the groups assigned

## assign bivariate color scale fills to quantile variable pairs

## Variables: 1, 3
bivariate_color_scale_var1_var3 %<>%
  separate(gr_var1_var3, into = c("mean_quantiles_variable_one", "mean_quantiles_variable_three"), sep = " - ") %>%
  mutate(mean_quantiles_variable_one = as.integer(mean_quantiles_variable_one),
         mean_quantiles_variable_three = as.integer(mean_quantiles_variable_three)
         )

legend <- ggplot() +
  geom_tile(
    data = bivariate_color_scale_var1_var3,
    mapping = aes(
      x = mean_quantiles_variable_three,
      y = mean_quantiles_variable_one,
      fill = fill_var1_var3)
  ) +
  scale_fill_identity() +
  labs(x = "Higher income (up to 40k) ->",
       y = "More active living environment ->") +
  theme_map() +
  # make font small enough
  theme(
    axis.title = element_text(size = 6)
  ) +
  # quadratic tiles
  coord_fixed()

legend

Map theme settings

default_background_color <- "transparent"
  default_font_color <- "black"
  default_font_family <- "Helvetica"
  
theme_map <- function(...) {
  default_background_color <- "transparent"
  default_font_color <- "black"
  default_font_family <- "Helvetica"
  
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    text = element_text(family = default_font_family,
                        color = default_font_color),
    # remove all axes
    axis.line = element_blank(),
    axis.text.x = element_blank(),
    axis.text.y = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    # add a subtle grid
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    # background colors
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = default_background_color,
                                   color = NA),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = default_background_color,
                                    color = NA),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = default_background_color,
                                     color = NA),
    # borders and margins
    plot.margin = unit(c(.5, .5, .2, .5), "cm"),
    panel.border = element_blank(),
    panel.spacing = unit(c(-.1, 0.2, .2, 0.2), "cm"),
    # titles
    legend.title = element_text(size = 11),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 22, hjust = 0,
                               color = default_font_color),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 15, hjust = 0.5,
                              color = default_font_color),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 10, hjust = 0.5,
                                 color = default_font_color,
                                 margin = margin(b = -0.1,
                                                 t = -0.1,
                                                 l = 2,
                                                 unit = "cm"),
                                 debug = F),
    # captions
    plot.caption = element_text(size = 7,
                                hjust = .5,
                                margin = margin(t = 0.2,
                                                b = 0,
                                                unit = "cm"),
                                color = "#939184"),
    ...
  )
}

map_var_1 <-   ggplot(
  # use the same dataset as before
  data = cropped_roads_var1_var3
  ) +
  # first: draw the relief
  # geom_raster(
  #   data = relief,
  #   aes(
  #     x = x,
  #     y = y,
  #     alpha = value
  #   )
  # ) +
  # use the "alpha hack" (as the "fill" aesthetic is already taken)
  scale_alpha(name = "",
              range = c(0.6, 0),
              guide = F) + # suppress legend
  # color municipalities according to their gini / income combination
  geom_sf(
    aes(
      fill = mean_quantiles_variable_one
    ),
    # use thin white stroke for municipalities
    color = "white",
    size = 0
  ) +
  # as the sf object municipality_prod_geo has a column with name "fill" that
  # contains the literal color as hex code for each municipality, we can use
  # scale_fill_identity here
  scale_fill_identity() +
  # use the Viridis color scale
  scale_fill_viridis(
    option = "magma",
    name = "Active living index",
    alpha = 0.8, # make fill a bit brighter
    begin = 0.1, # this option seems to be new (compared to 2016):
    # with this we can truncate the
    # color scale, so that extreme colors (very dark and very bright) are not
    # used, which makes the map a bit more aesthetic
    end = 0.9,
    discrete = T, # discrete classes, thus guide_legend instead of _colorbar
    direction = 1, # dark is lowest, yellow is highest
    guide = guide_legend(
     keyheight = unit(5, units = "mm"),
     title.position = "top",
     reverse = T # display highest income on top
  )) +
  # use thicker white stroke for cantons
  # geom_sf(
  #   data = canton_geo,
  #   fill = "transparent",
  #   color = "white",
  #   size = 0.5
  # ) +
  # # draw lakes in light blue
  # geom_sf(
  #   data = lake_geo,
  #   fill = "#D6F1FF",
  #   color = "transparent"
  # ) +
  # add titles
  labs(x = NULL,
         y = NULL#,
         #subtitle = "Montreal's active living",
         #title = paste0("Percent of people spending more than 30% of income",
         #                  " on housing vs. ratio of renting tenants, 2016"),
         #caption = "Fig. 1. Active living index vs. average property value"
       ) +
  # add the theme
  theme_map()
